[h1]DOM Tree[/h1]

The DOM represents a document as a tree structure.
HTML elements become interrelated [b]nodes [/b]in the tree.
All those nodes in the tree have some kind of relations among each other. 
Nodes can have [b]child [/b]nodes. Nodes on the same tree level are called [b]siblings[/b].
For example, consider the following structure: [img id="2773" width="100%"]
For the example above:
<html> has two children (<head>, <body>);
<head> has one child (<title>) and one parent (<html>);
<title> has one parent (<head>) and no children;
<body> has two children (<h1> and <a>) and one parent (<html>);
[note]It is important to understand the relationships between elements in an HTML document in order to be able to manipulate them with JavaScript.[/note]
